<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="93" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="93">Distribution and habitat.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="93">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Veranso-Libalah &amp; G. Kadereit" authorityYear="2019" baseAuthorityName="Veranso-Libalah &amp; G. Kadereit" baseAuthorityYear="2019" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Nothodissotis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Nothodissotis barteri" order="Myrtales" pageId="4" pageNumber="93" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="barteri">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="93">Nothodissotis barteri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is sparsely distributed in Cameroon (Ebo forest), south-eastern Equatorial Guinea (near Nsork), northern Gabon, and 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Príncipe">Principe</normalizedToken>
Island (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Distribution of Nothodissotis species." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.118.31572.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/269690" pageId="4" pageNumber="93">4</figureCitation>
). It occurs exclusively on rock outcrops at 370-1000 m elevation, mainly in low shrubby vegetation near the edge of the rocks (&quot;manteau arbustif&quot;) where it is locally dominant, and sometimes also as isolated plants in rocky grassland dominated by 
<taxonomicName authorityName="J. Raynal" authorityYear="1963" baseAuthorityName="Boeckeler" class="Monocotyledoneae" family="Cyperaceae" genus="Afrotrilepis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Afrotrilepis pilosa" order="Cyperales" pageId="4" pageNumber="93" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="pilosa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="93">Afrotrilepis pilosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Boeck.) J.Raynal (
<taxonomicName authorityName="J.Raynal" authorityYear="1963" baseAuthorityName="Gilly" class="Monocotyledoneae" family="Cyperaceae" genus="Afrotrilepis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Cyperales" pageId="4" pageNumber="93" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="family">Cyperaceae</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="93" type="phenology">
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="93">Phenology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="93">
Flowering recorded mainly from 
<normalizedToken originalValue="November–February">November-February</normalizedToken>
, once in August; fruits in March, 
<normalizedToken originalValue="May–June">May-June</normalizedToken>
, August, October and December.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="94" pageId="4" pageNumber="93" type="conservation status">
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="93">Conservation status.</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="94" pageId="4" pageNumber="93">
Vulnerable [VU B2ab(iii)]. The EOO of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Veranso-Libalah &amp; G. Kadereit" authorityYear="2019" baseAuthorityName="Veranso-Libalah &amp; G. Kadereit" baseAuthorityYear="2019" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Nothodissotis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Nothodissotis barteri" order="Myrtales" pageId="4" pageNumber="93" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="barteri">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="93">Nothodissotis barteri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is estimated to be 82,625 km2 (above the upper limit for Vulnerable status under sub-criterion B1) and its AOO to be 48 km2 (within the limit for Endangered under sub-criterion B2). The species is sparsely distributed in Cameroon, Equatorial Guinea, northern Gabon and 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Príncipe">Principe</normalizedToken>
island, and is restricted to rocky outcrops where it occurs in low shrubby vegetation or grassland. It is known from 21 collections representing eleven subpopulations, most of which (except three on 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Príncipe">Principe</normalizedToken>
island) lie outside protected areas. In most of its range, bushfires and agriculture (mostly pineapple plantations) represent the main threats to its habitat; planned tourism development in 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Príncipe">Principe</normalizedToken>
is another threat. A decline in habitat extent and quality is therefore expected. The eleven subpopulations represent a total of ten locations (sensu 
<bibRefCitation author="IUCN" journalOrPublisher="2. L. Reeve, London" pageId="10" pageNumber="99" refId="B6" refString="IUCN, 2012. IUCN Red List Categories and Criteria. Version 3.1 (2nd edn). IUCN Species Survival Commission, Gland &amp; Cambridge." title="IUCN Red List Categories and Criteria. Version 3.1 (2 nd edn). IUCN Species Survival Commission, Gland &amp; Cambridge." year="2012">IUCN 2012</bibRefCitation>
), fall 
<pageBreakToken pageId="5" pageNumber="94" start="start">ing</pageBreakToken>
within the limit for Vulnerable status, and the species is therefore assessed as Vulnerable under these conditions B2ab(iii).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="94" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="5" pageNumber="94">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="5" pageNumber="94">
This species, originally described from 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Príncipe">Principe</normalizedToken>
Island (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.title.42" author="Hooker, JD" editor="Oliver, D" journalOrPublisher="2. L. Reeve, London" pageId="10" pageNumber="99" pagination="439 - 464" refId="B5" refString="Hooker, JD, 1871. Melastomaceae. In: Oliver, D, Ed., Flora of tropical Africa, vol. 2. L. Reeve, London: 439 - 464, DOI: https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.title.42" title="Melastomaceae." url="https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.title.42" volumeTitle="Flora of tropical Africa, vol." year="1871">Hooker 1871</bibRefCitation>
), has since been reported from Gabon (
<bibRefCitation author="Jacques-Felix, H" journalOrPublisher="2. L. Reeve, London" pageId="10" pageNumber="99" refId="B9" refString="Jacques-Felix, H, 1983b. 25. Melastomatacees. In: Leroy JF (Ed.) Flore du Gabon. Museum National d'Histoire Naturelle, Paris." title="25. Melastomatacees. In: Leroy JF (Ed.) Flore du Gabon. Museum National d'Histoire Naturelle, Paris." year="1983 b">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Jacques-Félix">Jacques-Felix</normalizedToken>
1983b
</bibRefCitation>
) and Equatorial Guinea (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3989/ajbm.2002.v60.i2.95" author="Parmentier, I" journalOrPublisher="Anales del Jardin Botanico de Madrid" pageId="11" pageNumber="100" pagination="331 - 346" refId="B13" refString="Parmentier, I, Geerinck, D, 2003. Checklist of the Melastomataceae of Equatorial Guinea. Anales del Jardin Botanico de Madrid 60 (2): 331 - 346, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3989/ajbm.2002.v60.i2.95" title="Checklist of the Melastomataceae of Equatorial Guinea." url="https://doi.org/10.3989/ajbm.2002.v60.i2.95" volume="60" year="2003">Parmentier and Geerinck 2003</bibRefCitation>
). The collections cited above from Cameroon are the first for the country and represent an important range extension northwards.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="5" pageNumber="94">
The seeds of this species have not been described previously (e.g. 
